<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=2163&amp;p=18164#p18164"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Battery backed SRAM ??<br />Not only normal NES boards doesn't have a slot for battery, but also all games that want to write to the mapper will ERASE rom data.<br /></div><br /><br />There are chips like the Dallas DS1245 that are SRAM with an internal battery and power monitor.  But I think it'd be almost absurd to use it, unless you want NVRAM to write to.  Those chips are physically huge and fairly expensive.<br /><br />It's easy to prevent a write though, just don't hook memory up to the /write line.  <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />I'd say to go with FlashROM though.  You can get up to 512kB, 29F040 or 29C040.  And 29C256 if you want 32kB (no rewiring needed for that one).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Mon Oct 02, 2006 12:03 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
